<P>As they went along, Father Thomas, in who&s;e mind the expiration of the week appeared with all its horrors, pre&s;&s;ed them to ha&s;ten forward, telling them in general terms, that if they were not back in a week, dreadful con&s;equences might en&s;ue&mdash;and as it was full four days journey to Burgos, at the common rate of travelling, it was found expedient to put their hor&s;es to the pu&s;h.</P>
<P>The Baron could not comprehend what Father Thomas meant, nor would the latter tell him, but amu&s;ed him with a &s;tory of his own fiction. The truth was, Father Thomas knowing the warm, impetuous temper of the Baron, was afraid to tell him what pa&s;&s;ed in the vault, le&s;t it &s;hould rou&s;e him to &s;ome act of ra&s;hne&s;s that might de|feat all their projects, and had enjoined Alphon&s;o and the officer to be &s;ilent on that head.</P>
<P>They arrived at Burgos on the evening of the third day; and the urgency of the ca&s;e being a &s;ufficient excu&s;e, the officer that night made a faithful report to the corregidor, and Don Juan <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">earing the whole went <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> the king.&mdash;They viewed the armour, and Don Juan having it <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> in the proper places, &s;aid, he would bear witne&s;s to its being Gon&s;alvo's. The prie&s;t then gave an exact account of the &s;cene in the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> chamber&mdash;The king was horror &s;truck&mdash;Never&punc; &s;aid he, have I heard of &s;uch accumulated <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">. The Baron was like a per&s;on bereft of his <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">&mdash;he meditated&mdash;attempted to &s;peak&mdash;pau&s;ed <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">
