<P>Meantime the lady, a&s;&s;i&s;ted by Don Juan, came to her&s;elf&mdash;and &s;tared wildly round her.&mdash;Is he dead? &s;aid &s;he&mdash;Oh no! Is not this he? Alas! I have not &s;een my child the&s;e many years!&mdash;She then looked down eagerly on her &s;on, who, on his part, &s;eeing his friend Alphon|&s;o, exclaimed in ec&s;tacy&mdash;Good God! is this my Alphon&s;o?&mdash;Surely it is&mdash;Ah! where, Alphon&s;o where is the Baron de Rayo?&mdash;Hah! where&mdash;what &s;aid&s;t thou, my child? did you &s;ay the Ba|ron de Rayo? it cannot be&mdash;Ah, no!&mdash;my father&mdash;my beloved father is long &s;ince numbered with the dead&mdash;el&s;e I &s;hould not be here, nor you my child.&mdash;No&mdash;my father is now in company with tho&s;e chri&s;tian heroes, who&s;e valour and virtues adorned human nature, &s;inging hymns of glory to the Mo&s;t High!</P>
<P>While this was pa&s;&s;ing in the &s;ubterranean part of the ca&s;tle, the officer had &s;ummoned, in the king's name, the lord of the ca&s;tle to open the gates.&mdash;The Marquis, who had, in his con&s;ter|nation at the fir&s;t account of their arrival, pro|ceeded to the act of de&s;peration already men|tioned, was &s;ought for in vain over the ca&s;tle&mdash;Attendants ran up and down&mdash;and the Prior, per|ceiving the convent gate be&s;ieged by a troop, im|mediately betook him&s;elf to his wonted pa&s;&s;age to &s;eek the Marquis:&mdash;his route lay through <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">
